The planets are set to align again in 2021, although won’t be as close to one another as they will be in 2018.

If Tito was to try again then, the journey would take 80 days longer and require the shuttle to fly closer to the sun, adding radiation risks.

Nasa has previously said that the optimum time to launch a Mars mission would a ‘few months’ before Earth and Mars are closest together, a time astronomers call opposition. 

Tito announced his plans, dubbed Inspiration Mars, during a hearing at the House of Representatives subcommittee on space on Wednesday.

He said: ‘It would be a voyage of around 800 million miles around the sun in 501 days.

